&#xa0;
[normal]Written evidence submitted by  [bold]Shaare Zedek [bold]&#xa0;
[normal]Summary[bold]Shaare Zedek Medical Centre is a microcosm of 
[normal]the society that 
[normal]leaders strive to create in the region; a community of people from all religions, ethnicities and backgrounds who live and work together side by side regardless of their circumstances. 
[normal][1]
[normal]Through employment opportunities, 
[normal]institutional collaboration, 
[normal]medi
[normal]cal treatment and research, Shaare Zedek delivers a 
[normal]model of coexistence in action, often at great financial expense to the hospital. [2]
[normal]Vario
[normal]us research initiatives exist
[normal] specifically
[normal] to
[normal] advance the medical treatment of Palestinians and Arab patients. Me
[normal]dical departments including the Paediatric Dialysis Unit treat mo
[normal]re Arab patients than 
[normal]f
[normal]rom
[normal] any other ethnic background. [3]
[normal]Even d
[normal]uring times of political tension and violence
[normal],
[normal] the hospital continues to 
[normal]adhere to 
[normal]its principles of patient care without pre
[normal]judice. [4]
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]Shaare Zedek [bold]Medical Centre[bold]Shaare Zedek UK raises vital funds to support the work of the Shaare Zedek Medical Centre in Jerusalem. 
[normal]Literally meaning 
[normal]“Gates of Righteousness,” Shaare Zedek has responded to the needs of Jerusalem’s uniquely diverse population from its very first day of operation 
[normal]in 1902
[normal];
[normal] treating patients of every race, religio
[normal]n and nationality
[normal] regardless of financial circumstances. 
[normal]Medi
[normal]cal excellence, patient dignity and a compassionate individualised approach to all
[normal] are core to our
[normal] mission
[normal]. 
[normal]Additionally, t
[normal]he 
[normal]1,000 bed 
[normal]hospital maintains its reputation as an internationally-regarded research and teaching hospital, committed to advancing 
[normal]scientific progress, innovation and technology.
[normal] [5]
[normal]Shaare Zedek, with its century-long tradition of offering quality medical care to all in Jerusalem, has been a highly positive force in the city’
[normal]s development
[normal] and has contributed greatly to residents’ qua
[normal]lity of life.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] Today, it is considered to be in the top echelon of med
[normal]ical institutions in Israel, despite receiving 
[normal]no government funding
[normal] 
[normal]for equipment, development or research. 
[normal][6]
[normal]Coexistence as a way of life[bold]Visiting dignitaries
[normal],
[normal] including British Parliamentarians
[normal],
[normal] often ask about 
[normal]efforts taken to advance
[normal] coexistence at the hospital. Coexistence is a way of life 
[normal]at Shaare Zedek. 
[normal]Patient ethnicity is not recorded upon admission but the hospital 
[normal]estimates that 
[normal]the ethnic makeup of 
[normal]its patient population is very similar to th
[normal]at
[normal] of Jerusalem as a whole; 
[normal]approximately 70
[normal]% Jewish, 30% Arab. Our patients are referred from all over Israel and surrounding areas including 
[normal]t
[normal]he 
[normal]Palesti
[normal]nian Territories
[normal] and other countries including the United 
[normal]Arab 
[normal]Emirates
[normal].
[normal] [7]
[normal]Our staff also 
[normal]closely mirrors
[normal] Jerusalem’s ethnic and religious composition.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] We have several senior staff members from the Arab and Palestinian communities, including our chief cardiothoracic surgeon, a senior anesthetist, a senior uro
[normal]logist, and a senior cardiologist.
[normal] [8]
[normal]Certain departments of the hospital have a patient mix which varies significantly from the average for a variety of reasons.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] For instance, approximately two-thirds of the patients in our 
[normal]Paediatric
[normal] Dialysis Unit are Arabs, because of a genetic predisposition in that population to kidney disease.
[normal] 
[normal]I
[normal]n order to better meet the edu
[normal]cational and social needs of the
[normal]se
[normal] yo
[normal]ung patients and their families, the 
[normal]Paediatric
[normal] Dialysis Unit
[normal] has an Arab social worker 
[normal]and an Arab teacher on staff. 
[normal] [9]
[normal]Interestingly, while in the “outside world,” there is minimal contact between ultra-Orthodox Jews and Arabs, in the 
[normal]P
[normal]a
[normal]ediatric
[normal] Dialysis Unit, 
[normal]patients and families 
[normal]from both cultures 
[normal]mix freely.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] Families with children su
[normal]ffering from kidney disease find that they have much more in common than that which divides them.
[normal] This sense of community was witnessed by 
[normal]Councillor
[normal] Vikki Slade on a recent visit to the hospital:
[normal] [9]
[normal]“These children have to come into the hospital on a 
[normal]daily or alternate daily basis, something which has an incredible impact on the family lives of those involved. I was heartened to watch parents sit with children from the opposite side of the political divide while their own parents went to pick up other 
[normal]siblings from school or leave the bedside for other reasons.”
[normal] [10]
[normal]Shaare Zedek’s approach is not to ignore religious and ethnic differences; it is rather to show respect for them.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] This approach is demonstrated in a number of areas.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] A perfect example t
[normal]akes place in the M
[normal]uslim
[normal] month of Ramadan, when religiously observant Muslims fast from sunrise to sunset.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] Shaare
[normal] Zedek provides a special 
[normal]meal for its Muslim staff members, scheduled to begin precisely at sunset.
[normal] 
[normal][11]
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Arab[bold] patients[bold]The policy 
[normal]of 
[normal]“political blindness” comes at a great cost to the hospital.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] While Israeli citizens are entitled by law to health coverage through one of the country’s health funds, non-citizens like those who com
[normal]e from the Palestinian Authority
[normal] have no such coverage and
[normal] often these cases are completely uninsured.
[normal] [12]
[normal]While severe limitations have been placed on the number of patients coming into Israel from the P
[normal]alestinian 
[normal]A
[normal]uthority
[normal], there are still a significant number of Palestinians being treated in Israeli hospitals
[normal], including Shaare Zedek.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] The cost to the hospital to treat these largely uninsured patients is well in excess of $100,000 per year.
[normal] [13]
[normal]Despite this
[normal], it is our pledge as a modern medical 
[normal]cent
[normal]re
[normal] driven 
[normal]by compassion and not politics 
[normal]to ensure that when a
[normal] patient arrives at our doors in need of help, he or she will not be deprived.
[normal] 
[normal][14]
[normal]A story which illustrates th
[normal]is approach is t
[normal]hat of a three year 
[normal]old girl rushed to Shaare Zedek from Nablus with severe kidney failure. The close relationship between the h
[normal]ead of the hospital in Nablus and the head of 
[normal]Paediatric
[normal] Nephrology at Shaare Zedek meant one phone call ensured a crash team were waiting for her on arrival. She died on the operating table but the medical team managed to stabilize her and brought her bac
[normal]k to life after which she made 
[normal]a remarkable
[normal] recovery in the care of the 
[normal]Paediatric
[normal] Dialysis Unit. 
[normal]This life saving collaboration was only possible 
[normal]because of the 
[normal]close relationship between the 
[normal]two 
[normal]doctors. Shaare Zedek 
[normal]was
[normal] 
[normal]fully 
[normal]aware that there was no aut
[normal]horization from the Palestinian Authority to treat her
[normal] and even if such authorization had been given it would not have covered most of the cost of the treatment. 
[normal]Shaare Ze
[normal]dek covered the full cost of the girl’s
[normal] treatment. 
[normal]Such stories are a regular occurre
[normal]nce at Shaare Zedek
[normal] and are part of the hospital’s contribution to peace
[normal]ful coexistence
[normal].  
[normal][15]
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Coexistence at times of political conflict[bold]Shaare Zedek is not immune to the effects of terrorism. The direct impact on the number of patients and the 
[normal]increased demand for emergency and trauma medicine is immense. During such periods staff-
[normal]often 
[normal]including those whose family members have been victims of attacks- continue their work on the 
[normal]understanding that those who enter our doors 
[normal]are patients first and
[normal] foremost
[normal] and the duty of doctors and nurses is to heal.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] 
[normal]Following a shooting during the Second Intifada one young patient recounted how a team of Arab and Jewish doctors had brought her back to life:
[normal] [16]
[normal]“
[normal]A bullet ripped through my chest and into my lun
[normal]g. Two women were killed during that attack and dozens more, beside me, were wounded.
[normal] 
[normal]I was taken by ambulance to Shaare Zedek Medical Centre and by the time we made it to the hospital, I had no pulse and no blood pressure. I was considered dead on arrival
[normal]. Through the skilled hands of Dr. Shuli Silberman and Dr. Mahar Deeb, a Jewish and Arab doctor working together, they performed a miracle and brought me back to life. After the surgery, was a long recovery process. My after-care specialist, Dr. Salah Odat
[normal]allah, stayed by my side through my stay in the ICU and then in the regular ward. But that was not enough. During my stay we formed a strong bond and when I was given permission to return to Chicago, he insisted he fly back with me to ensure my safe return
[normal].
[normal]”
[normal] [17]
[normal]Shaare Zedek also treated a number of Arab victims of terror attacks during the Intifada.
[normal] One victim, 
[normal]Ibrahim
[normal],
[normal] explained the importance of a social workers’ support for his brother after they were both brought to Shaare Zedek 
[normal]suffering injuries fr
[normal]om a bus bombing
[normal]:
[normal] [18]
[normal] “For him to see just how much the staff cares about him, the way everyone wants to help, has made a big difference to him.”
[normal] [19]
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Research [bold]&#xa0;[bold]In the area of research, we have conducted a number of studies in cooperation with 
[normal]Jordanian and Palestinian physicians and hospitals, including a comparative study of the use of pain medication for cancer patients in various institutions, and a genetics study to identify mutations associated with a high risk of breast cancer.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] Cooperati
[normal]ve research with Palestinian institutions has been curtailed to some extent because the risk of terrorism has impeded travel, but staff members on both sides are doing their best to continue working together.
[normal] [20]
[normal]Being 
[normal]based in the heart of Jerusalem
[normal],
[normal] Sha
[normal]are Zedek is fortunate to have a diverse population of people with a wide ethnic pool
[normal] which provides
[normal] a 
[normal]fantastic 
[normal]resou
[normal]rce for research. Recent studies 
[normal]looking specifically at Jewish and Arab populations 
[normal]include research into 
[normal]children
[normal]’
[normal]s smoking habits 
[normal] and
[normal] diabetes
[normal].
[normal] [21]
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]A major focus of research int
[normal]o inherited diseases
[normal] is identifying the mutations responsible for genetic diseases in children. In Jerusalem, marriage between relatives or within a small ethnic group is still common and
[normal],
[normal] combined with large 
[normal]family size, this results in a higher frequency of genetic diseases in children. Some diseases are common, e.g. Tay Sachs, which is now prevented by prior testing, but many of these often devastating diseases are specific to a particular family. Advances i
[normal]n genetic technology make it possible to identify the mutation causing the disease. This can help the family prevent further affected children (e.g. by 
[normal]pre-implantation genetic diagnosis
[normal]) and also provides important insights into the functions of various g
[normal]en
[normal]es. We have already identified seven new disease genes in the past three
[normal] years.
[normal] [22]
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Research activity in the Medical Genetics Institute includes collaboration with Palestinian colleagues to determine inherited mutations that affect breast cancer risk 
[normal]in Arab women
[normal]. The Breast Health Centre is 
[normal]also 
[normal]working on a comparative study examining the characteristics 
[normal]and stages of diagnosis 
[normal]of Arab 
[normal]and Jewish 
[normal]breast cancer patients 
[normal]in Jerusalem
[normal].
[normal] [23]
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]Shaare Zedek &amp; UK [bold]Government [bold]Shaare Zedek’s collaborative 
[normal]approach to medicine was first raised in Parliament by Lord Turnberg during a Parliamentary debate in 2003:
[normal] [24]
[normal] [bold]“I was very encouraged by a meeting that I had with representatives of the Shaare Zedek Hospital in Jerusalem, who described efforts that they
[normal] were making to work with a major hospital in Amman in Jordan and in Ramallah in the Palestinian territories. They were developing plans jointly to provide humanitarian aid of a medical type in a co-ordinated way for the survivors of conflicts in Iraq and 
[normal]other places in the Middle East. Will it be possible for the UK to work with those organisations to support them and others which are working in a co-ordinated operation?”
[normal] [25]
[normal]This project did not receive support from UK Government but contact remains be
[normal]tween the institutions. 
[normal][26]
[normal]We would welcome a visit by the 
[normal]Committee to the hospital to gain a greater understanding of Shaare Zedek’s work in medical collaboration across communities. 
[normal][27
