[normal]Appendices[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]Letter written for Shaare Zedek UK newsletter from Councillor PPC Vikki Slade following a visit to Shaare Zedek, September 2013
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]As foreign aid and field hospitals arrive in the Philippines this week I am reminded of my inspirat
[normal]ional trip to Israel and Palestine last month and the account from two members of the Israeli rescue mission to Haiti after their devastating earthquake.
[normal]Our LDFI (Liberal Democrat Friends of Israel) Parliamentary visit was intended to provide an understa
[normal]nding of the geo-political situation in Israel and Palestine and we were privileged to meet a range of political and social figures on both sides along with families living in Jerusalem who hosted us for their Shabbat dinners.
[normal]Our first encounter at the h
[normal]ospital was the Paediatric Dialysis Unit where I was struck by the sheer number of children from all ethnic backgrounds who suffer from genetic kidney disorders. We were told that this has become prevalent partly due to limited integration in small communi
[normal]ties. These children have to come into the hospital on a daily or alternate daily basis, something which has an incredible impact on the family lives of those involved. I was heartened to watch parents sit with children from the opposite side of the politi
[normal]cal divide while their own parents went to pick up other siblings from school or leave the bedside for other reasons.
[normal]Elsewhere in the hospital we toured the Emergency department, funded by generous donations and named for a British family who support a n
[normal]umber of medical establishments in Israel. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Its design is unusual in that it forms a series of concentric circles, helping specialists to work across the unit more effectively, and it is built underground to make it resilient to the attacks that were a fea
[normal]ture of Jerusalem in the past.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]As a first time visitor to Jerusalem, the Shaare Zedek Medical Centre provided a real ray of hope among the political turmoil surrounding its historic building. A place of love, welcome to all whatever their race or religio
[normal]n. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Of all the places we visited in the country, this was the place I witnessed the world in one place – staff, patients and visitors representing almost every nation of the world. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Coming together with love and showing humanity's similarities rather than 
[normal]focusing on our differences.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Cllr Vikki Slade
[normal]Prospective Parliamentary Candidate
[normal]For UK General Election in Mid Dorset &amp; North Poole
[normal]&#xa0;
